---
title: "FAQ"
---

## Authentication

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="How do I authenticate my requests?">
    Every request must include your API key in the `Authorization` header as a Bearer token:

    ```bash
    Authorization: Bearer tf-live-4a8f2c1e9b3d7e6a
    ```

    Requests without a valid key return a `401 Unauthorized` error.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="What does a 401 error mean?">
    A `401` response means the API key is either missing or invalid. Check that:

    - The `Authorization` header is present in the request.
    - The value starts with `Bearer ` (note the space).
    - The key itself is correct and has not been revoked.
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

## Projects

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="Do I need a project before creating tasks?">
    Yes. Every task must belong to a project. You must call `POST /projects` first and use the returned `project_id` when creating tasks. Sending a `project_id` that does not exist returns a `404` error.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="I lost my project_id. How do I find it again?">
    The current version of the API does not include a `GET /projects` endpoint. If you lose a `project_id`, you cannot retrieve it through the API. Always store IDs on your side after creation.

    <Note>
      A `GET /projects` endpoint is planned as a future improvement.
    </Note>
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Can I update or delete a project?">
    Not in the current version. There are no endpoints for updating or deleting projects. These are planned improvements for a future release.
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

## Tasks

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="What is the default status of a new task?">
    All tasks are created with status `pending` by default. You cannot set a different status at creation time — use `PATCH /tasks/{task_id}` to update it afterward.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="What status values are allowed?">
    There are exactly three valid values:

    - `pending` — task has not been started.
    - `in_progress` — task is actively being worked on.
    - `done` — task has been completed.

    Any other value returns a `400 Bad Request`.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Can I update multiple fields at once?">
    Yes. `PATCH /tasks/{task_id}` accepts `status`, `title`, and `description` in the same request. At least one field must be provided — an empty body returns a `400` error.

    ```json
    {
      "status": "in_progress",
      "title": "Write introduction and quickstart pages"
    }
    ```
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Is it possible to recover a deleted task?">
    No. Deletion via `DELETE /tasks/{task_id}` is permanent and cannot be undone. There is no trash or archive feature.

    <Warning>
      Always confirm the correct `task_id` before sending a DELETE request.
    </Warning>
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Is there pagination for task lists?">
    No. `GET /projects/{project_id}/tasks` returns all tasks at once. There are no `limit`, `offset`, or page parameters. For projects with a large number of tasks, consider handling pagination on your side.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Can I filter tasks by status?">
    No. `GET /projects/{project_id}/tasks` always returns all tasks in a project. 
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

## Errors

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="What does the error response look like?">
    All error responses follow the same structure:

    ```json
    {
      "error": "Not Found",
      "message": "No project found with project_id 'abc123'."
    }
    ```

    The `error` field is a short type, and `message` provides a human-readable explanation.
  </Accordion>

  <Accordion title="Quick reference: common error codes">
    - `400` Bad Request — Missing required field, invalid status value, or empty PATCH body.
    - `401` Unauthorized — Missing or invalid API key in the Authorization header.
    - `404` Not Found — The `project_id` or `task_id` does not exist.
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>
